        Stop 1 — Bernauer Straße Memorial

Imagine standing on a quiet residential street one morning in August 1961 — and watching your city split in two. Overnight, barbed wire and concrete appeared right here, turning neighbors into enemies and homes into front lines.

Bernauer Straße became a symbol of division. The Wall cut directly across the middle of the street: people on one side found themselves trapped in the East, while their front doors literally opened into the West.

In the first desperate days, residents leapt from windows to freedom — others were caught or killed. Entire buildings were bricked up. The church that once stood nearby, the Church of Reconciliation, was trapped in the no-man’s-land and eventually destroyed.

Today, this memorial preserves a section of the original death strip: the watchtower, the border fence, and the space where guards once patrolled with orders to shoot. Yet it’s also a place of peace — where Berliners come to remember, reflect, and honor those who risked everything to cross from darkness into light.

Take a moment to walk along the preserved Wall section. Try to imagine what it meant to live here — divided by politics, but united in spirit.

